  "prompt": "Does water exist on mars?",
  "response": "Yes, water does exist on Mars, primarily in the form of ice. Observations by various spacecraft and rovers have confirmed the presence of water ice at the polar ice caps and beneath the surface in various locations. In addition, there are signs of liquid water, including recurring slope lineae (dark streaks on slopes) that may result from briny liquid water flowing intermittently, though this remains a topic of ongoing research and debate. In 2018, radar data from the European Space Agency's Mars Express mission detected what appears to be a subsurface lake of liquid water beneath the south polar ice cap. Overall, while the current environment on Mars is harsh and primarily cold and dry, evidence suggests that water, in its various forms, is present on the planet.",
